SIMPLE: spill
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spill
<hw>Spill</hw> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[⟦root⟧170. Cf.
<er>Spell</er> a splinter.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bit of wood split
off; a splinter.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A slender piece of anything.</def> Specifically:
--⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A peg or pin for plugging a hole, as in a cask; a
spile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A metallic rod or pin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A small roll of paper, or slip of wood, used as a
lamplighter, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>One of the thick laths or poles
driven horizontally ahead on top of a set of the main timbering in
advancing a level in loose ground.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> forepole; spile{4}.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A little sum of money.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spill
<hw>Spill</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spilt</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧lt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover or decorate with
slender pieces of wood, metal, ivory, etc.; to inlay.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spill
<hw>Spill</hw> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spilled</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧ld)</pr>, or
<conjf>Spilt</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦icr⟧lt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>spillen</ets>,
usually, to destroy, AS. <ets>spillan</ets>, <ets>spildan</ets>, to
destroy; akin to Icel. <ets>spilla</ets> to destroy, Sw.
<ets>spilla</ets> to spill, Dan. <ets>spilde</ets>, LG. & D.
<ets>spillen</ets> to squander, OHG. <ets>spildan</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To destroy; to kill; to put an end to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And gave him to the queen, all at her will⟦br⟧
To choose whether she would him save or <qex>spill</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Greater glory think [it] to save than <qex>spill</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mar; to injure; to deface; hence, to destroy by
misuse; to waste.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They [the colors] disfigure the stuff and <qex>spill</qex> the
whole workmanship.</q> <rj><qau>Puttenham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Spill</qex> not the morning, the quintessence of day, in
recreations.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To suffer to fall or run out of a vessel; to lose,
or suffer to be scattered; -- applied to fluids and to substances whose
particles are small and loose; <as>as, to <ex>spill</ex> water from a
pail; to <ex>spill</ex> quicksilver from a vessel; to <ex>spill</ex>
powder from a paper; to <ex>spill</ex> sand or flour</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Spill</xex> differs from <xex>pour</xex> in
expressing accidental loss, -- a loss or waste contrary to
purpose.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to flow out and be lost or wasted; to shed,
or suffer to be shed, as in battle or in manslaughter; <as>as, a man
<ex>spills</ex> another's blood, or his own blood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And to revenge his blood so justly <qex>spilt</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To relieve a sail from the
pressure of the wind, so that it can be more easily reefed or furled, or
to lessen the strain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spilling line</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a rope
used for spilling, or dislodging, the wind from the belly of a
sail.</cd> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- Spill, n. An instance of spilling. Oil spill, an accidental
release of oil, usually into the ocean, due to damage to an oil tanker
or uncontrolled release from an underwater well. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spill
<hw>Spill</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be destroyed,
ruined, or wasted; to come to ruin; to perish; to waste.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That thou wilt suffer innocents to <qex>spill</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be shed; to run over; to fall out, and be lost or
wasted.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He was so topful of himself, that he let it
<xex>spill</xex> on all the company.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I.
Watts.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spiller</ent>⟦br⟧
